{"ts":"2026-02-20T02:01:48.174716963Z","seq":293,"event":"message_complete","session_id":"chat-2026-02-20T0201-fp8gy7","data":{"message_id":"msg-c922de5d-6dd9-4694-96c5-70d213bcf74c","full_response":"Crucible uses wikilinks to build a knowledge graph by treating each note as a node in the graph and each wikilink as an edge connecting related nodes. When a user writes `[[Note Name]]` in a markdown note, Crucible interprets this as a reference to another note. The system then parses these wikilinks to establish relationships between notes, forming a structured network of interconnected knowledge.\n\nThis knowledge graph enables several powerful features:\n- **Graph Traversal**: Users can explore related concepts by following links from one note to another.\n- **Semantic Relationships**: The graph captures not just direct references but also indirect connections, enabling discovery of related topics.\n- **Search and Discovery**: Queries can leverage the graph structure to find notes that are semantically or contextually related, even if they don't contain the exact search term.\n- **Contextual Understanding**: By analyzing the link structure, Crucible can infer relationships between ideas, such as \"causes,\" \"components,\" or \"related concepts.\"\n\nAdditionally, Crucible uses block-level embeddings to enhance search capabilities, allowing for fine-grained semantic search within each note. This combination of wikilinks and embeddings enables a rich, interconnected knowledge base where users can navigate and discover information in a way that mirrors human thought patterns.\n\nIn summary, wikilinks serve as the foundational structure for the knowledge graph, while semantic search and graph traversal provide the tools to explore and leverage the relationships between notes.","prompt_tokens":0,"completion_tokens":0,"total_tokens":0}}
